choices.text:
by foot/bike/car, a short distance (3-4 hours) away is Karakol, the former capitol of Russian Turkestan — a quaint city with lots of pedestrian access. Karakol hosts another Central Asian favorite sport — dog racing. I stayed there for a week in an old Soviet building and surrounded by horse stables.

The trail then turns back west to go over Zhumu Pass to Batken through the picturesque village of Shekhan. Local villagers are friendly and welcoming, they offer you everything – “we are selling, we have food, come in our yurta, sit and drink tea, come and look at the view.”

This side trip is extraneous unless you are shipping a motorbike out of Uzbekistan. The road is not accessible by motor vehicle, two small excursion vehicles are the largest accumulation of metal on the pass.

Coming off of those passes, you may have experienced the full range of emotions – loneliness, solitude, exhaustion, anger, elation, pride. In order to return to civilization after riding the Pamir Highway, you must face your fears again, and conquer the last mountain pass of the Pamir Highway: the Ak-Baital.

Ak-Baital Pass (officially called Torugart – which is actually a border post crossing) sit at 3,752 meters.

Standing at the top, one felt a distance from “normal” world. To the west is the newly-renamed Wakhan Valley;
